IRS990.Desc: MOUNTAIN-PACIFIC QUALITY HEALTH IS A NON-PROFIT CORPORATION THAT PARTNERS WITHIN OUR COMMUNITIES TO PROVIDE SOLUTIONS FOR BETTER HEALTH. WE SERVICE MONTANA, WYOMING, ALASKA, HAWAII, AND THE U.S. PACIFIC TERRITORIES OF GUAM, AMERICAN SAMOA, AND THE COMMONWEALTH OF THE NORTHERN MARIANA ISLANDS.MOUNTAIN-PACIFIC PROVIDES MEDICAID UTILIZATION REVIEW AND MANAGEMENT SERVICES FOR THE MONTANA DEPARTMENT OF PUBLIC HEALTH AND HUMAN SERVICES. THROUGH OUR REVIEW PROCESS WE STRIVE TO ENABLE EACH MEDICAID CLIENT TO HAVE HIS OR HER NEEDS MET IN THE MOST APPROPRIATE, COST-EFFECTIVE SETTING, USING THE MOST APPROPRIATE MEDICAL SERVICE, EQUIPMENT, SUPPLIES, AND MEDICATION.

ProgSrvcAccomActy2Grp.Desc: MOUNTAIN-PACIFIC QUALITY HEALTH'S SERVICE AREA INVOLVES SUPPORTING THE CENTERS FOR MEDICARE & MEDICAID SERVICES' (CMS) INITIATIVES. WE ARE ONE OF 14 QUALITY INNOVATION NETWORK-QUALITY IMPROVEMENT ORGANIZATIONS (QIN-QIOS). WE PARTNER WITH HEALTH CARE PROVIDERS, PRACTITIONERS, STAKEHOLDERS, AND PATIENTS ON A VARIETY OF QUALITY IMPROVEMENT INITIATIVES TO ACHIEVE BETTER CARE, BETTER POPULATION HEALTH, AND LOWER HEALTH CARE COSTS.

ProgSrvcAccomActy3Grp.Desc: MOUNTAIN-PACIFIC QUALITY HEALTH HAS DEVELOPED SERVICES THAT COMBINE CLINICAL BEST PRACTICES, THE USE OF HEALTH INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (HIT) AND ELECTRONIC DATA WITH STRATEGIC AND INNOVATIVE APPROACHES TO HELP TRANSFORM HEALTH CARE DELIVERY, QUALITY REPORTING AND PATIENT SAFETY. CONSULTING SERVICES INCLUDE: - HEALTH CARE PERFORMANCE REPORTING - HEALTH CARE OPTIMIZATION AND TRANSFORMATION - POPULATION HEALTH IMPROVEMENT - HIT TECHNICAL SUPPORT - PROJECT MANAGEMENT AND LEADERSHIP

SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE ORGANIZATION QUALIFIES FOR THE CHARITABLE CONTRIBUTION DEDUCTION UNDER SECTION 170(B)(1)(A). IN ADDITION, THE ORGANIZATION IS EXEMPT FROM FEDERAL INCOME TAXES UNDER SECTION 501(C)(3) OF THE INTERNAL REVENUE CODE AND STATE INCOME TAXES. HOWEVER, INCOME FROM CERTAIN ACTIVITIES NOT DIRECTLY RELATED TO THE ORGANIZATION'S TAX-EXEMPT PURPOSE IS SUBJECT TO TAXATION ON UNRELATED BUSINESS INCOME. UNDER THE TAX CUTS AND JOBS ACT, ANY COSTS INCURRED BY A NONPROFIT ORGANIZATION TO PROVIDE PARKING FOR EMPLOYEES BECAME UNRELATED BUSINESS INCOME BEGINNING JANUARY 1, 2018. THE ORGANIZATION PAID STATE AND FEDERAL CORPORATE TAXES RELATED TO THIS UNRELATED BUSINESS INCOME TOTALING $17,552 IN THE FISCAL YEAR ENDED JUNE 30, 2019. ON DECEMBER 20, 2019, THE PRESIDENT SIGNED INTO LAW THE FURTHER CONSOLIDATED APPROPRIATIONS ACT THAT RETROACTIVELY REPEALED THE EMPLOYEE PARKING BENEFIT TAX TREATMENT FOR TAX-EXEMPT ORGANIZATIONS. THE ORGANIZATION HAS FILED AMENDED TAX RETURNS REQUESTING THE REFUND OF ALL FEDERAL AND STATE TAX, INTEREST, AND PENALTY PAYMENTS. THE ORGANIZATION RECEIVED THE FINAL REFUND PAYMENT IN JULY 2021. THE ORGANIZATION BELIEVES THAT INCOME TAX FILING POSITIONS WILL BE SUSTAINED UPON EXAMINATION AND DOES NOT ANTICIPATE ANY ADJUSTMENTS THAT WOULD RESULT IN A MATERIAL ADVERSE EFFECT ON ITS FINANCIAL CONDITION, RESULTS OF OPERATIONS OR CASH FLOWS. ACCORDINGLY, THE ORGANIZATION HAS NOT RECORDED ANY RESERVES OR RELATED ACCRUALS FOR INTEREST OR PENALTIES FOR UNCERTAIN INCOME TAX POSITIONS AS OF JUNE 30, 2022. THE ORGANIZATION'S POLICY IS TO CLASSIFY INCOME TAX RELATED INTEREST AND PENALTIES TO INTEREST EXPENSE AND MISCELLANEOUS EXPENSE, RESPECTIVELY, WHEN APPLICABLE.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION A, LINE 4
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE ORGANIZATION'S BYLAWS WERE AMENDED DURING THE YEAR. BELOW ARE THE SIGNIFICANT CHANGES. 1. THE COMPOSITION OF THE BYLAWS COMMITTEE APPOINTED BY THE PRESIDENT MUST BE MADE UP OF AT LEAST FOUR (4) INDEPENDENT DIRECTORS. 2. THE EMPLOYEE RETIREMENT COMMITTEE MUST BE MADE UP OF AT LEAST FOUR INDEPENDENT DIRECTORS, AS APPOINTED BY THE PRESIDENT, AND FOUR (4) EMPLOYEE REPRESENTATIVES ELECTED BY MPQH TO SERVE IN AN ADVISORY ROLE (NON-VOTING). THE CHIEF EXECUTIVE OFFICER IS A VOTING MEMBER OF THE COMMITTEE. 3. THE COMPOSITION OF THE PUBLIC POLICY COMMITTEE APPOINTED BY THE PRESIDENT MUST BE MADE UP OF AT LEAST FOUR (4) INDEPENDENT DIRECTORS. 4. THE BOARD SHALL MAKE REASONABLE EFFORTS TO INCLUDE REPRESENTATION FROM EACH STAKEHOLDER STATE IN THE STANDING COMMITTEES.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION B, LINE 11B
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE CFO REVIEWS THE FORM 990 FOR ACCURACY AND RECOMMENDS THE RETURN FOR PROCESSING. THE BOARD IS PROVIDED THE OPPORTUNITY FOR REVIEW AND INPUT PRIOR TO FILING. GOING FORWARD, THE REVIEW RESPONSIBILITIES WILL MOVE TO THE CAO.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION B, LINE 12C
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE CONFLICT OF INTEREST POLICY COVERS THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS, CEO, CFO, COO, CIO, AND KEY EMPLOYEES. WHEN A CONFLICT OF INTEREST ARISES WITH AN EMPLOYEE, THE CEO, COMPLIANCE OFFICER, AND HR DIRECTOR REVIEW THE CONFLICT AND THE COMPLIANCE OFFICER ULTIMATELY DETERMINES IF A CONFLICT EXISTS. IF A CONFLICT OF INTEREST ARISES WITH A BOARD MEMBER, THE BOARD COMPLIANCE COMMITTEE AND BOARD MANAGER REVIEW THE CONFLICT. THOSE DETERMINED TO HAVE A CONFLICT ARE EXCLUDED FROM DELIBERATIONS AND DECISIONS. OTHER RESTRICTIONS MAY BE IMPOSED DEPENDING ON THE CIRCUMSTANCES AND LEVEL OF RISK ASSOCIATED WITH THE CONFLICT.

SupplementalInformationDetail.FormAndLineReferenceDesc: FORM 990, PART VI, SECTION B, LINE 15
SupplementalInformationDetail.ExplanationTxt: THE BOARD OF DIRECTORS APPROVES THE COMPENSATION OF THE CEO. FOR OFFICERS OR KEY EMPLOYEES, THE ORGANIZATION USES AN INDEPENDENT SALARY SURVEY TO DETERMINE THE COMPENSATION AND THE COMPENSATION IS APPROVED BY THE CEO.
